\section{Warrior (Ver 2.0)}
\label{warrior}
d3 14
a16 74
\index{warrior|(}
\index{skills!warrior|(}
A warrior is one who learns the art of combat. The skill is not so
much concerned with weapon skills as with combat skills. As such
weapons not used in melee combat (\eg bows) and uses of weapons
that are not melee oriented (\eg throwing weapons or attacking
from behind or close combat, although it is expected that a warrior
will have some skill in close and ranged combat) receive no bonus
from this skill.  To understand the warrior skill it is important to
realize that unlike other skills where advancement is dependent
equally on knowledge and practice, for a warrior advancement must
revolve around practice primarily and knowledge of special moves and
tactics is less important.  Thus a warrior does not necessarily know
more about combat than another fighter, but is more practiced at all
the possible variations on combat.

The advantages a warrior receives in melee combat accrue because of
their experience in combat both against and with all types of
weapons. They train on all terrains and in all combinations (\eg one
on one, one on two, two on one etc.) and in the process learn the
advantages and disadvantages of each weapon and each combat situation.

More importantly, because the warrior spends so much of their time
training in weapons and in combat, the individual weapon skills become
more than a set of well learned thrusts, cuts, parries, and ripostes --
they become reactions. Thus a warrior no longer decides their action
whether it be right or wrong, they react, and because of their
training their reactions are the best possible given the weapon they
are using, the weapon they are facing, and the situation they are
in.

Obviously the skill teaches more than just the appropriate reactions;
a warrior will become able to choose the best weapon and tactics for
any given engagement, they will be able to make the best use of the
terrain, and the other relevant factors to improve their chances of
success. But ultimately once the preliminary decisions have been made,
when weapon meets weapon it is their trained reactions that give the
warrior the real advantage in combat.

As a result of the dedication to training required to become a warrior
the skill has become associated with other codes of conduct, such as
chivalry and honourable combat, which may govern a warrior's whole
outlook on life.  But as should be clear it is not necessary to have a
code of ethics to be a warrior, the skill is a result of training,
although it may prove difficult to be trained without being
indoctrinated by the teacher, and as such many warriors will come out
of training with a specific code of ethics.  Equally obvious should be
the fact that there is no specific reason why a warrior cannot become
an assassin or an assassin become a warrior.  Of course many warriors
will be trained to abhor assassins and assassination. The warrior
skill will give no advantage to situations where the attack is more
akin to assassination than combat.

Nevertheless some of the results of the training could easily be
confused with an ethical code, and this is perhaps why the warrior
skill is often considered part of an honourable or chivalric code. To
explain this, it is necessary to look at how the warrior trains.  They
spend most of their time in combat --- not deadly combat, but
practice.  This is when they learn how to use their knowledge of
combat and tactics. The purpose of this combat is to practice the
skill of combat; thus once an opponent is defeated the combat is over
and a new one begins.  In short the warrior's natural instincts in
combat are to defeat the opponent, not necessarily kill them.

The natural result of this kind of training is that a warrior gains no
advantages when his opponent cannot reply (due to surprise, stunning,
disarming, always remembering unarmed combat as a legitimate weapon,
etc.). This is an interactive skill; to gain their bonuses a warrior
needs an active opponent. As is obvious from the above the warrior
loses all their skill bonuses if they attack an opponent who cannot
reply; they simply have not trained for such a situation (that's an
executioner's or assassin's job).  While such an attack may be in
character, as the warrior becomes more skilled their instincts will
push them towards ``fair'' combat (not to mention their ego).
